    %p The anaphoric pronoun was never allowed to stand on its own in its original nominative/accusative case form, so an old demonstrative pronoun он- with endings was used to stand in its place. This nominative form is to be avoided when at all possible.
    %p The original accusative was replaced by the genitive, avoiding the problem of the lone anaphoric pronoun. In the lative form of the old accusative, however, an epenthetic /n/ was acquired to allow the nominative form to stand on its own, in a way. The /n/ likely came from the prepositions that usually preceded nouns in this case, several of which ended in an /n/ which was lost at a later point (e.g., Novegradian во “into” ← Common Slavic *vъn, although this /n/ reemerges in certain situations).
    %p There is also a second set of third person pronouns, this one derived from the former demonstrative *to, the same that cliticizes to nouns to topicalize them. True to this function, however, this set cannot be used to refer to third person nouns that are not topicalized. Within the realm of topicalized nouns, however, то and оне exist in free variation.
