= section "Determiners" do
  %p Common determiners in Novegradian include #{t "вехе", "véhe"} “all”, #{t "многе", "mnóge"} “many, much”, #{t "кожне", "kóźne"} “each, every”, #{t "таде", "tadé"} “such”, #{t "видоре", "vidóre"} “other”, #{t "саме", "sáme"} “same”, and #{t "оба", "óba"} “both”.
  %p Кожне, таде, видоре, and саме are all treated as normal adjectives. Многе, despite how it looks, is not an adjective and does not decline (although the form многие, borrowed from Russian and declined like a plural definite adjective, is used to mean “many people”); there is an adjective многе, but it means “multiple”. Оба is declined exactly the same way as the numeral дова “two”, including having a feminine form #{t "обѣ", "óbě"}. Вехе takes a pronominal declension like ше or мой, but with a very large number of irregularities:
