  %p The first consonant varies between /β ~ Ø/, the root-internal vowel between /i ~ e ~ o/, and the second consonant between /x ~ γ ~ j/. The rules are basically as follows:
  %ol
    %li The vowel is /e/ when stressed, /i/ when unstressed and the following syllable contains a front vowel, and /o/ when unstressed and the following syllable contains a back vowel.
    %li If the root-internal vowel is /o/, the first consonant is zero. If the vowel is anything else, the first consonant is /β/.
    %li If the syllable immediately after the root is unstressed, the root-final consonant is /x/. If the syllable is stressed and contains a back vowel, the root-final consonant is /γ/. If it is stressed and contains a front vowel, the root-final consonant is /j/.
  %p The neuter form, #{t "оғо", "oğó"}, can be used by itself as a pronoun to mean “everything”. The plural, #{t "вие", "vijé"}, can be used to mean “everyone”.

