  = section "Indefinite Forms" do
    %p The indefinite forms were for the most part discussed previously. Most of them are formed from the corresponding interrogative with the addition of -ш, which in the case of the “person”, “thing”, and “time” categories results in some minor alterations to the root, generally preserving an older form<sup>6</sup>.
    %p The “determiner” and “amount” forms feature the prefix *ně-, which in Common Slavic was a common marker of indefiniteness, but in Novegradian gradually fell out of use and is now limited to just these two words.
    %p The difference in meaning between the adjective нѣкотре “some” and the quantifier нѣколкѣ “some amount (of)” is rather subtle and will be explained in section 15.7. Very generally, the former represents a value that is determinate or fixed, but simple not mentioned, while the latter represents a value that is random or indeterminate.
    %p The gap in the “reason” category can be filled using expressions such as #{t "по кадей-еш приѕинѣ", "po kadéi-eś pridzíně"} “for some reason (lit. “for some sort of reason”).
  
  = section "Negative Forms" do
    %p The negative forms, as previously discussed, are generally formed by adding не- to the interrogative forms, sometimes causing shifts in stress toward the prefix. The “origin” form introduces an epenthetic /β/ to prevent hiatus.
    %p The form #{t "некойда", "nekóida"} “never” is completely regular in the standard, though the form #{t "некода", "nékoda"} is a very widespread dialectical/poetic variant.
    %p The negative determiner #{t "не ше", "ne śé"} “no [noun]” is always written as two words, though phonetically it acts as one—the particle не (always pronounced [nə]) and the declining demonstrative adjective: #{t "не ша дужа", "ne śá duźá"} “no person, not one person”<sup>7</sup>. The original Common Slavic *ni has been lost in Novegradian.
    %p The negative amount gap can be filled with #{t "некадо сколицестуо", "nekadó skolícestuo"} “no [kind of] amount” or #{t "не ше сколицестуо", "ne śé skolícestuo"} “no amount”. The negative reason gap can be filled with #{t "по некадѣ приѕинѣ", "po nekadě́ pridzíně"} “for no reason”.
  
  = section "Universal Forms" do
    %p The universal forms convey the basic sense of “all” or “every”—a totality.
    %p The determiner category can be filled either by the adjective #{t "кожне", "kóźne"} “every” or the pronominal adjective #{t "вехе", "véhe"} “all”, depending on whether a distributive or total sense is needed.
    %p The other single-word categories are filled by forms of вехе or derivatives of it. The “person” and “thing” categories use the plural and neuter declensions of вехе respectively. The forms #{t "веходе", "vehodé"} “everywhere” and #{t "вехода", "vehodá"} “always” come from вехе plus the base of the interrogative: вехода (#{abbrev 'CS'} form *vьхъ-gъda ← *vьxъ + *(kъ)-gъda, where the *kъ- is the same interrogative element found in most other interrogative words). The adjective of quality #{t "веяде", "veiáde"} “every kind” comes from “all” + (ка)де.
    %p There is also the adverb #{t "веғаде", "veğáde"} “everywhere, all over”, with a similar meaning to веходе. The former implies more of a scattering, while the later suggests complete coverage.
    %p All other categories are periphrastic. One of the more interesting constructions is #{t "на вие ходѣ", "na vijé hódě"} “to everywhere, in all directions”, a reanalysis of веходе as вехе “all” + ходе “direction”. Of course, a variety of other alternatives exist as well. The most common forms for each category are: #{t "на вие ходѣ", "na vijé hódě"} “in all directions” (direction), #{t "од виех ход", "od vijéh hód"} “from all directions” (origin), #{t "вие сколицестуа", "vijé skolicestuá"} “all amounts [of]”, #{t "виѣми позобам", "vijě́mi pozóbam"} “by all means” (way), #{t "по виех приѕинѣх", "po vijéh pridzíněh"} “for all reasons” (reason).
   
