  = section "Indeterminate Forms" do
    %p The indeterminate forms indicate, logically, the indeterminate nature of the item or quality in question, without regard to its exact identity or quantity. Its basic sense is like that of English “any”.
    %p For most of the correlative categories, it is formed by suffixing #{t "-ко", "-ko"} to the interrogative form, in writing separated by a hyphen. In the case of declining forms like цой-ко, хой-ко, and каде-ко, the stem is fully declined first, and then the clitic is added, as was the case for the indefinite forms in -ш.
    %p Colloquially, the clitic reduces to just -к, and the stress shifts to the vowel immediately before it: #{t "койда-к", "koidá-k"} “whenever”, #{t "како-к", "kakó-k"} “however”, #{t "ково-к", "kovó-k"} “whomever (#{abbrev 'acc'})”. However, the nominative forms хой-ко and цой-ко tend to retain the /o/, as well as any other form ending in a consonant.
    %p Disregarding the contradictory name, there is also an indeterminate determiner; it is the adjective #{t "котре", "kótre"} without any clitic, previously seen as the interrogative “which?”.
    %p The two gaps are most often filled by #{t "од котра мѣсту", "od kótra mě́stu"} “from any place” and #{t "по кадѣ-ко приѕинѣ", "po kadě́-ko pridzíně"} “for whatever kind of reason”.
  
  = section "Deficient Forms" do
    %p The deficient forms suggest a lack of sufficient quantity, or more generally a small quantity, though not necessarily in a negative light.
    %p All existing deficient correlatives are formed by prefixing #{t "мало-", "malo-"} to the interrogative stem. Otherwise they decline regularly.
    %p Alternative phrasings are possible for all forms, most commonly using the adverb #{t "немноге", "nemnóge"} “not many, few” plus a noun: #{t "немноге луд", "nemnóge lúd"} “few people”. The gaps are almost always filled with немноге constructions: #{t "немноге род", "nemnóge ród"} “few kinds [of]”, #{t "од немноге мѣсот", "od nemnóge mě́sot"} “from few places”, etc.
  
  = section "Other Forms" do
    %p A small number of other correlatives exist that do not fit neatly into the tables above, or else require a class all to themselves.
    %p There is a single locative based on the stem <i>*ien-</i> (← #{abbrev 'CS'} *in- “other”): #{t "енде", "iendé"} “elsewhere, somewhere else”. This stem has a cognate adjective #{t "ене", "iéne"}, although it is no longer productive and is only found in the conjunction/preposition #{t "ене неж", "iéne neź"} “different from, unlike”. A second cognate adjective, #{t "енаке", "ienáke"} “another”, is similarly unproductive and is only found in a few fixed expressions (although its adverbial form #{t "енакѣ", "ienákě"} “otherwise” is quite common).
    %p The adjective of universal quality #{t "веяде", "veiáde"} “every kind of” has a notable dialectical variant #{t "хаде", "hadé"}. This form, common throughout the Novegradian north and east, actually shares a common origin with веяде; both ultimately derive from Old Novegradian вьхаде. Хаде is not accepted in formal writing, but is very common in speech in these areas.
    %p Novegradian also frequently makes use of rhyming compounds based on the proximal and distal forms of various correlatives to indicate a sort of random universality or widespread distribution. These are more dependent on keeping up the S~T pattern than using actual correlatives, so such “compounds” make use of a number of nonce words: #{t "суде-туде", "sudé-tudé"} “here and there”, #{t "суди-туди", "sudí-tudí"} “hither and thither, back and forth”, #{t "оцуда-остуда", "ocúda-ostúda"} “hence and thence, from all over”, #{t "сойда-тойда", "sóida-tóida"} “now and then, occasionally”, and #{t "солкѣ-толкѣ", "sólkě-tólkě"} “a random amount, a jumble”. These are all acceptable in the standard language, though none of the nonce forms are allowed in isolation.

= section "Relative Pronouns" do
  %p There are two sorts of relative constructions in use in Novegradian.
  %p When the relative clause is pegged to a noun, there are two relative adjectives that may be used: #{t "котре", "kótre"} and #{t "какове", "kákove"}. The former links a relative clause specifically to the noun it modifies (e.g., “This is the book that I do not like”). The latter links the relative clause to a quality of the noun it modifies, or to the class it forms a part of (e.g., “This is the book, the type of which I do not like”/”This is the kind of book I don’t like”). Both decline as regular adjectives, agreeing in gender and number with the noun they modify, but in case with the noun’s position in the relative clause.
  %p However, when there is no noun to subordinate the clause to (e.g., “I know that he’s coming tomorrow” or “Remember who helped you”), a different construction must be used. Here the relativizer consists of two parts: a form of #{t "то", "tó"}, declined according to its function in the main clause, and a relative pronoun (generally цой or хой), declined according to its function in the subclause. То declines using just the neuter and plural pronominal endings, identical to то when used as a personal pronoun, except with animacy distinguished in the accusative.
